I am a curator, researcher and writer with an interest in exploring the intersection of art, science and culture through collaborative and integrative work. Having been at the National Academy of Sciences for over 20 years and serving as the director of Cultural Programs of the National Academy of Sciences for most of that time, the question that I am asked most often is what kind of training did I receive to prepare me for the position I now occupy.  This is not an easy question to answer and, in fact, brings up a major issue in traditional education and research models.  As a student, I was like many of the young people I encounter today who are 1) interested in more than one thing; 2) curious; and 3) felt the need to explore more than what the educational system allows.  My undergraduate career path meandered through computer science and engineering, music (I studied concert violin), journalism, accounting and eventually photography.  I then pursued graduate degrees in both studio arts and museum studies.  My interests are to better understand the relationship between disciplines and the benefits of collaborative and integrative practices in education, research (both art and science) and society.
